ce:section.ce:para:
Nanostructured carbon materials manifest themselves in a variety of nano and quantum scale structures e.g. graphene, reduced graphene oxide (rGO), carbon quantum dots (CQDs), graphene quantum dots (GQDs), carbon nanotubes (CNTs), fullerene, graphene nanoribbons (GNR) etc., which are efficient photosensitive materials and have been employed for photodetection application over the past decade [11,12]. The optical behavior and charge carrier transport in these carbon nanostructures differ from one to another considerably which makes them effective for a broad range of optoelectronic applications like light-emitting diodes, photodetectors, imaging applications, etc. Especially, the photodetection performance of carbon nanostructures can be well enhanced by suitable heterostructuring with semiconductors having different structures and optical properties [13,14]. This topic of research has been the center point of scientific investigation over the past couple of years. Almost all NC materials have been investigated in conjunction with conventional bulk semiconductor materials and their nanostructures (Fig. 1
                     ) like Si/Ge [15], III-V/II-VI semiconductor alloys [16,17], 2D materials [18], perovskites [19], transition metal dichalcogenides (TMDCs) [20], polymers [21], etc. For photodetection application. Fig. 1 demonstrates the versatility in device configuration, materials combination and technology in present state-of-the-art PDs comprising NC and conventional semiconductor nanostructures. As shown in Fig. 2
                     , the past ten years have witnessed the important developments of the carbonaceous heterojunction PDs, from individual carbonaceous material PDs to heterojunction PDs, and further developing waveguide/antenna/metamaterial integrated PDs with gradual improvement in spectral response characteristics (from DUV to THz). With the rapid development of the intelligent era, NC heterojunction PDs will certainly innovate to the direction of intelligence, diversification, and functionality. Therefore, an illustrated review concerning these heterostructures based photodetectors is of utmost necessity for the present research community and scientific readers to design the next generation device for futuristic artificial intelligence (AI) technology.
